School uniforms were found inside the factory, including for top private schools in Durban.

While the electricity meter was connected legally, according to officials, the wiring was deemed a hazard and the Building Inspectorate advised the owner of the clothing fac­tory to vacate the premises.

The city said it was using a multidisciplinary approach to deal with bad buildings, which  involved numerous departments within the city including the metro police, Land Use, Building Inspectorate, Durban Solid Waste, and Business Support, among others.

“There are two teams, A and B, in operation, and in this team there are close to 90 people who start at 6.30am and move through different zones,” said Estice.

The municipality said the campaign was part of an ­effort to regenerate and renew the CBD of the inner city and other key economic hubs. 

“The Inner City Regeneration Programme offers eThekwini municipality an exciting, yet challenging, opportunity for regeneration of its main economic hubs. 

“This operation tackles illegal trading, illegal businesses, illegal dumping and other contraventions,” said the head of the Development Planning and Environment Management Unit, Musa Mbhele. “Our message to landowners and landlords is to have a safe environment for people to work in, which abides by the by-laws of the municipality to ensure safety.”

Sudesh Naicker of Land Use Management said the zoning of the property allowed for an industrial building, but it did not allow for excessive heavy industrial use that would cause smoke, dust or fumes. 

“What we found here is completely unacceptable, therefore we will need to ­investigate and request that this building be shut down until they are able to comply,” Naicker said.

Officials said that when they called the owner of the building, he said he had not been aware of what was going on inside. He was given 30 days to comply.
The Mercury